**simple, practical guide** to run and configure NGINX on your system (Linux / Ubuntu / WSL).

---

# 1️⃣ Install NGINX

sudo apt update
sudo apt install nginx

Check version:

nginx -v

---

# 2️⃣ Start / Stop NGINX

sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl stop nginx
sudo systemctl restart nginx

Enable auto-start:

sudo systemctl enable nginx

---

# 3️⃣ Test It

Open browser:

http://localhost

👉 You should see: **“Welcome to nginx!”**

---

# 4️⃣ Important Files

| Purpose       | Path                          |
| ------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Main config   | `/etc/nginx/nginx.conf`       |
| Site configs  | `/etc/nginx/sites-available/` |
| Enabled sites | `/etc/nginx/sites-enabled/`   |

---

# 5️⃣ Create Your Config (Reverse Proxy)

## Step A: Create new config
## Step B: Enable it
## Step C: Test config

sudo nginx -t

👉 If OK:
syntax is ok
test is successful

---

## Step D: Reload NGINX

sudo systemctl reload nginx

---

# 6️⃣ Connect to Your C++ Server

Run your C++ app on:

http://localhost:8080

Then access via NGINX:

http://localhost/api?key=test

---

# ⚠️ Common Issues

### ❌ Port already in use

sudo lsof -i :80

---

### ❌ Permission denied

Use `sudo` for config changes

---

### ❌ Config not applied

Always run:

sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl reload nginx

---

# Mental Model

Client → NGINX (port 80) → C++ backend (port 8080)

---

# Pro Tips

* Use different routes:

/api  → C++ backend
/static → files

* Add logs:

access_log /var/log/nginx/access.log;

---

# One-line summary

Install → create config → enable → test → reload → done

